Seasonal creek, only runs a few months of the year (January to May). The creek varies in width but mostly is 6 to 12/14 inches wide and 2 to 5 inches deep. Water was diverted using a bucket to dip water for stock.
The landowner continues to expect Pre-1914 rights to continue to be intact for future years if and when more water returns to this seasonal gulch. This is not a significant nor a substantial diversion.

DIVERSION_AND_USE_COMMENT: The water that comes into Cloak Lake is either winter run-off off of 150 acres approximately, and tail water of these pastures during irrigation season.  The water source of this irrigation is the Big Springs Irrigation District.If the water level of Cloak Lake is near spill-way height releases can be made into Barton Lake, then to Spring Lake for irrigation supplementation. The State should make more effort to encourage this practice, because the pollution goes into my pasture fields, which consume it, feeding the grass and the cattle, where it can't reach the stream.  My experience is that the State employees may be most concerned about my losing it into the stream, which doesn't happen. It runs into the large city reservoir, from which it is pumped, or another reservoir of mine and then also re-pumped to the fields.

FORM_NAME: Report of Licensee
WATER_CONSERVE_DESC: I divert and store my tailwater, in a small reservoir, preventing it from returning to the Shasta R.  I then pipe it by gravity to the inlet bay of my pump, when I know the pump will be running. In 2015 the tailwater substituted 20 acre feet of recycled water in lieu of River water. Use a time clock for the pump so the water won't be wasted at night. This pipeline has a flow meter to measure tailwater for the season.
ADDITIONAL_REMARKS: The volume of water used for the season is determined by the electric pump, which was calibrated by an engineering firm hired by our power co.  We replace the pump last year with a new one which was rated for the same volume flow and head.  I daily record the hours of use, then with the GPM of the pump, come up with the daily acre-feet of water diverted, less the recycled water.

FORM_NAME: Supplemental Statement of Water Diversion and Use
WATER_CONSERVE_DESC: I divert and store my tailwater, in a small reservoir, preventing it from returning to the Shasta R.  I then pipe it by gravity to the inlet bay for my pump, when I know the pump will be running.  In 2015 the tailwater substituted 41 acre feet of recycled water in lieu of River water.  Use a time clock for the pump so the water won't be wasted at night from the irrigated pasture.  This pipeline has a flow meter to measure tailwater for the season.
ADDITIONAL_REMARKS: The volume of water used for the season is determined by the electric pump, which was calibrated by an engineering firm hired by our power co.  We replaced the pump last year with a new one which was rated for the same volume flow and head.  I daily record the hours of use, then with the GPM of the pump, come up with the daily acre-feet of water diverted, less the recycled water.
WELL_LOCATION: NE 1/4 of NE 1/4 sec. 33, t. 45 N, r. 6 W, mdb m

FORM_NAME: Supplemental Statement of Water Diversion and Use
ADDITIONAL_REMARKS:
Water comes from springs and pond directly above my property. Natural historic flow is into meadow. Prior to subdivision rancher who owned property diverted water from springs into ditches on edge of meadow in order to keep meadow dry enough to hay. Water in ditches kept meadow subirrigated. I built small (600 square feet surface area) pond on my property. Water flows from pond into existing ditch along edge of meadow, preventing meadow from becoming marshy. Water flows off my property and returns underground. Livestock use pond and ditch as water source.

Parks Creek and Shasta River water is stored together in Dwinnell Reservoir/Shasta River Dam No 60 (Lake Shastina).  The reported amounts of water used under the permits includes water provided to the City of Montague in certain months when the City has no other available supply and water released at certain times for fish and wildlife enhancement flows as a result of litigation and coordination with CA DF&W and NOAA.  Amount of water used is reported as an allocated percentage of total water released from the dam, but does not include the amounts released for prior rights (3264 acre ft.)

DIVERSION_AND_USE_COMMENT: Water from this source is an emergency reserve supply for municipal purposes. During the reporting period, no water was consumed from the North Well. The well was only run for maintenance and water quality testing. The North Well facility was demolished and replaced from 5/16 to 4/17. The amount diverted in March is estimated by multiplying the pump capacity of 615 gpm by 1 hour of run time. A flow meter was installed during the upgrade.
WATER_CONSERVE_DESC: The City of Yreka implemented Stage 2 ""Water Alert"" of the City's Water Shortage Contingency plan on August 2014 to September 2016 to comply with State regulations in response to ongoing drought conditions in California. Stage 2 implemented a 3-day per week mandatory watering schedule and increased water use restrictions on all water customers in the City's water service area.
ADDITIONAL_REMARKS: (10)Although the City does employ water conservation efforts, the ""Amount of Water Conserved"" is listed as 0 gallons since the source is used as an emergency reserve supply only. Note: The Pumping facility is currently being replaced and upgraded to improve reliability.

ADDITIONAL_REMARKS: Water comes from springs and pond directly above my property. Natural historic flow is into meadow. Prior to subdivision rancher who owned property diverted water from springs into ditches on edge of meadow in order to keep meadow dry enough to hay. Water in ditches kept meadow subirrigated. I built small (600 square feet surface area) pond on my property. Water flows from pond into existing ditch along edge of meadow, preventing meadow from becoming marshy. Water flows off my property and returns underground. Livestock use pond and ditch as water source.

WATER_CONSERVE_DESC: I divert and store my tailwater, in a small reservoir, preventing it from returning to the Shasta R.  I then pipe it by gravity to the inlet bay of my pump, when I know the pump will be running. In 2015 the tailwater substituted 41 acre feet of recycled water in lieu of River water. Use a time clock for the pump so the water won't be wasted at night. This pipeline has a flow meter to measure tailwater for the season.
ADDITIONAL_REMARKS: The volume of water used for the season is determined by the electric pump, which was calibrated by an engineering firm hired by our power co.  We replace the pump last year with a new one which was rated for the same volume flow and head.  I daily record the hours of use, then with the GPM of the pump, come up with the daily acre-feet of water diverted, less the recycled water.

FORM_NAME: Report of Licensee
DIVERSION_AND_USE_COMMENT: The water comes down a creek from underground surfaces and then goes back underground.  This water is used for household use.  We do not live at the ranch so I am estimating that we go to the ranch approximately 20 days in the year  and use the water from the well to drink, bathe, flush toilets etc.  In a good year with sufficient rain, the lower field lake will fill up.   in the past 20 years, the upper lake has only filled twice and then has dissapated into the creek within a month.  In the 1990's before the drought, the lake would fill and stay filled.  These lakes when filled (seldom) are not used for irrigation.
ADDITIONAL_REMARKS: We do not have a reservoir.  The upper lake that existed in the past 20 years has not filled in the past years except for 2017 and 2018. The amount of time the lakes were fill  was for approximately 2 months and the water was never used for irrigation etc.  The drought has severely affected the growth of the hay and alfalfa and also the grazing of the cattle. This year the crops were so affected that the cattle were brought in to graze what little did grow.
WELL_LOCATION: NE 1/4 of NE 1/4 sec. 21, t. 44 N, r. 6 W, mdb m
